{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T19:07:12.185601+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-20T19:07:13.034345+00:00", "id": 19669636, "conceptrecid": "19669635", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669636", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669635", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19669636", "metadata": {"title": "Urine Concentrating Ability and Renal Structure of Insectivorous Bats", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669636", "publication_date": "1978", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Maximumurine concentratingability was determined for 11 species of insectivorous bats by water-deprivationexperiments. Mean maximumconcentrations ranged from 2,640 to 4,340 milliosmols/kg water. Renal indices involved with medullary thickness were highly correlated with urine concentrating ability (for example, r = .919 for the ratio of inner medullary zone:cortex, IM/C). Mean maximum urine concentrating abilities for six additional species were predicted from the following equation: mean maximum osmolality (mosmol/kg) = 658 + 558 (IM/C). The insectivorous bats limited to more arid habitats possessed better renal adaptationsfor water conservation.Under naturalconditions arid-adaptedspecies drinkwhen water is available; however, indirect evidence suggests that some may be able to survive long periods without water.", "access_right": "open", "creators": [{"name": "Geluso, K. N.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/ba6fa9cc637287477345aa44a7951bfd", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/c1aa053379e11de0b74131d5f54fb46ef489e5a9150c79a02e64fc9ef21c0a57", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/SNQSQGKK", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/SNQSQGKK", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "